column168: Original comments:  Package removed from system flow, wet/ripped carton. Package does not have any Hazmat markings, tags or orientation arrows. The drum was then placed in a salvage drum standing up to prevent any leakage. Going forward we are going to review the process with our staff so that only hazmat trained personal are handling these packages and inspecting them.

Would recommend smaller box, more packing, and clips for paint can.

AN EMPLOYEE WAS HAULING TWO 1,000 GALLON ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS DOWN A COUNTY ROAD. HE WAS TRYING TO STAY OFF THE ROADWAY AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE TO ALLOW VEHICLES TO PASS. THE TIRES ON AMMONIA NURSE TANKS ARE DESIGNED TO BE USED IN FIELDS AND ARE ONLY RATED FOR A MAXIMUM SPEED OF 25 MPH. ONE OF THE TIRE IN THE REAR TANK ENTERED A WASHOUT IN THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD WHICH WAS BELIEVED TO BE ENOUGH OF A BUMP TO CAUSE THE TANK TO FLIP OVER. WHEN THE TANK FLIPPED, THE VAPOR VALVES ON THE TOP OF TANK CRACKED, ALLOWING AMMONIA VAPOR TO ESCAPE. THE RELEASE WAS VERY SLOW, BUT COULD NOT BE STOPPED. THE WIND WAS BLOWING THE VAPOR IN A SAFE DIRECTION SO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ON SCENE DECIDED TO JUST ALLOW THE AMMONIA TO DISSIPATE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE RELEASE WAS FOR A DURATION OF APPROXIMATELY 5 HOURS.
column169: I WILL USE THIS INCIDENT AS AN EXAMPLE IN FUTURE TRAINING'S AS TO WHY IT IS IMPORTANT TO KEEP EVERY TIRE ON THE BLACKTOP OF CONCRETE WHEN HAULING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. EMPLOYEES WILL BE TRAINED THAT IT DOESN’T MATTER IF THEY HOLD UP TRAFFIC ON THE ROADS, THAT PUBLIC SAFETY TAKES PRIORITY AND NOT TO VEER OFF THE ROAD TO ALLOW VEHICLES TO PASS.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: Used Aircraft Fuel Probes were being shipped back to the originating American Airlines location after being reviewed by Engineering in Charlotte (CLT).  The probes were properly packaged to be shipped via ground.  In completing the FedEx shipping information, the Materials Logistics Specialist (MLS) unintentionally clicked on "air" out of habit rather than selecting "ground".  This set the shipment up for carriage by air on FedEx rather than by ground as intended.  The package had not been prepared correctly for transport by air thus creating the violation.  The parts were picked up by FedEx and transported via Cargo Aircraft to DFW.
column169: Perhaps a pop-up in the FedEx software that states, "You have selected for this shipment to be transported via aircraft.  Are you sure that is what you want to do?"  Better diligence on the part of shipper personnel or a means to double check what is being shipped by a second person who can validate what is being shipped.

column168: 2 Naval Aviators returning from training at NAS Norfolk offered their life vests with survival gear as checked baggage.  The bags had strap handles to carry them and attached to one strap handle on each bag was a clear plastic pouch containing a Shipper's Declaration of Dangerous Goods and a Class 9 label affixed to the outside of the clear plastic pouch.  The Shipper's Declaration indicated UN2990, Life-Saving Appliances, Self Inflating and Additional Handling Information of "Store in cool, well-ventilated area away from fire hazards and sources of heat/ignition.  Do not drop or rough handle.  ERG #171 Carbon Dioxide, 2.2; Cartridges, Signal, 1.4S; Signal Devices, Hand, 1.4S".  Unfortunately, the Ticket Agent checking in the Passengers did not notice the Shipper's Declarations attached to the handles of the bags or the Class 9 Hazard labels nor did any of the Ramp personnel in ORF as they were loading the bags onto the aircraft.  Upon arrival of the American Eagle Flight 4102 operated by Envoy Airlines into Chicago O'Hare (ORD) Airport, the Class 9 labels were noted by Envoy Ramp personnel upon unloading and the bags were stopped from further transportation.  The Naval Aviators did not tell the Agents about the contents of their bags nor did they indicate the pouch attached to the handle of the bag.
column169: American Airlines has taken steps to provide additional guidance to personnel in ORF.  Bulletins were posted by the Station General Manager. column168: THE TRAIN TRACKS RUN PARALLEL TO ROUTE 88 AT THE RR CROSSING WHERE THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED. HEADING WEST ON 88 TOWARDS THE ACCIDENT LOCATION, THE TRAIN TRACKS COME UP FROM AND AROUND A BEND JUST BEFORE THE RR CROSSING/ACCIDENT LOCATION. THIS RESULTS IN A RELATIVELY SHORT LINE OF SIGHT FOR THE TRUCK DRIVER. TRAIN SPEED AT THIS INTERSECTION IS BELIEVED TO HAVE RECENTLY BEEN INCREASED AND WE UNDERSTAND THAT THERE HAVE BEEN SEVERAL ACCIDENTS AT THIS SAME INTERSECTION OVER THE PAST SEVERAL YEARS, WITH MANY IF NOT MOST OF THE ACCIDENTS INVOLVING A TRAIN HEADING THE SAME DIRECTION (WEST). OUR DRIVER STOPPED TO MAKE LEFT TURN INTO CUSTOMER’S LOT. DRIVER TURNED 180 DEGREES OVER HIS LEFT SHOULDER (BEHIND HIM) AND LOOKED DOWN IN THE TRACKS BUT DID NOT SEE A TRAIN APPROACHING. TRAIN CAME AROUND CORNER OF TRACK AS THE TRUCK WAS IN THE TURN. THERE ARE NO LIGHTS OR GATES TO WARN THE TRUCK DRIVER THAT THERE IS A TRAIN APPROACHING. ENGINEER DID NOT BLOW HORN TO INDICATE HE WAS IN THE AREA UNTIL JUST BEFORE IMPACT. TRAIN STRUCK TRUCK BEHIND SLEEPER AT THE TRAILER. TRAIN RUPTURED TANK CAUSING HCL RELEASE. SEE PHOTOS OF THE AREA AND WHERE IMPACT/RUPTURE OCCURRED.  PRODUCT RELEASED FROM TRAILER ALMOST IMMEDIATELY ON TO GROUND UNDER AND AROUND TRACKS. CLEAN UP CREWS MITIGATED THE RELEASE BY NEUTRALIZING THE PRODUCT IMMEDIATELY WITH LIME THEN REMOVING ANY “PUDDLES” VIA A VAC TRUCK. A VAC TRUCK ALSO WAS USED AT THE SCENE TO SUCK OUT ANY REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TANK AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE RINSED WITH WATER BEFORE MOVING OFFSITE.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE INCLUDE REQUIRING THE RR TO INSTALL LIGHTS AND GATES AND INSTRUCT THEIR ENGINEERS TO BLOW HORNS BEFORE DURING AND AFTER THE BLIND BEND IN THE TRACKS. THIS WORLD WARN DRIVERS OF THEIR PRESENCE. THERE HAVE BEEN PERVIOUS ACCIDENTS AT THE SAME CROSSING IN THE PAST (WITH THE TRAIN COMING FROM THE SAME DIRECTION) AND IT SEEMS THAT GATES WOULD PREVENT A SIMILAR EVENT FROM HAPPENING AGAIN. THERE ARE A FEW BUSINESSES IN THE AREA AND TRUCKS NEED TO HAVE ACCESS TO THEM. ANOTHER RECOMMENDATION IS THE REQUIRE THE RR TO REDUCE TRAIN SPEED. KUHNLE BROTHERS UNDERSTANDS THAT THE SECTION OF TRACK AT ISSUE HAS A HIGHER SPEED LIMIT THAN THE SECTION OF TRACK FURTHER TO THE WEST IN VESTABURG. IT ALSO UNDERSTANDS THAT THE SECTION OF TRACK AT ISSUE (I.E. WHERE THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED) WAS RECENTLY THE SUBJECT OF AN INCREASED SPEED LIMIT.  ALL KUHNLE BROTHERS DRIVERS WERE REQUIRED TO ATTEND A SAFETY MEETING FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT. TOPICS INCLUDED TIME AND SPACE MANAGEMENT, AND RAIL ROAD CROSSING SAFETY AND RULES AMONG OTHER TOPICS. THE MEETING WAS HELD ON APRIL 2ST, BUT ALL DRIVERS HAD BEEN CONTACTED AFTER THE INCIDENT TO REMIND THEM OF THE RULES OF SAFE CROSSING.

column168: UNLEADED FUEL OVERFILLED. THE NL TANK HAS TWO DROPS AND IT APPEARED TO BE TWO LARGE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS MANIFOLDED TOGETHER BELOW GROUND. UPON ARRIVAL, TTE DRIVER STUCK THE FIRST TANK AND MEASURED 79” (SAFE FILL WAS 3,526 GALLONS). DRIVER SAFELY DROPPED COMPARTMENT #1 OF HIS TRAILER CONTAINING 3,300 GALLONS IN TO THIS DROP. THINKING THAT THE OTHER NL DROP WAS A SECOND SEPARATE TANK, DRIVER STUCK THIS TANK AND MEASURED 80” (SAFE FILL WAS APPROXIMATELY 3,500 AS WELL). UPON DROPPING COMPARTMENT #2 (1,100 GALLONS), 15 TO 16 GALLONS OF NL FUEL WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE SECOND DROP, SPEWING ON TO THE GROUND. APPROXIMATELY 2-3 GALLONS ENTERED IN TO THE STORM DRAIN, OMI ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED AT 6:06 AM. OMI AND HAZMAT INTERNATIONAL MANAGED THE SPILL REMEDIATION. THE STORM DRAIN AND LIFT STATION WERE WASHED DOWN, CONTAMINATED WATER WAS VACUUMED UP AND MICRO-BLAZE WAS SPRAYED OVER THE IMPACTED AREAS. A LARGE AREA OF EARTHEN MATERIALS LOCATED AT THE BASE OF THE RETENTION POND WAS HYDRO-EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED FROM THE SCENE TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT CONROE 7 INDUSTRIAL LANDFILL. FISCHER & ARNOLD TOOK SAMPLES OF THE EARTHEN MATERIALS FOR PROFILING PURPOSES. 8 YARDS OF DIRT WERE UTILIZED TO BACK-FILL THE RETENTION POND. EROSION MATTING WAS PLACED OUT AND HYDRO-SEEDING WA THEN PERFORMED.
column169: FUEL DELIVERY DRIVERS MUST PAY CLOSE ATTENTION WHEN READING THE SAFE FILL CHART FOR USTS AT DELIVERY LOCATIONS. THIS OVERSIGHT WAS 100% ON THE DRIVER DELIVERING FUEL TO THIS STORE.

column168: THE DRIVER ESTIMATED LENGTH OF HOSE AND CONNECT THE HOSES TOGETHER ON THE DOCK. THEN HE PASSED HOSE ONTO THE VESSEL. THE DRIVER DID NOT HAVE ENOUGH HOSE TO MAKE THE CONNECTION. SO HE UNCAPPED END ON THE DOCK. THERE WAS RESIDUAL FUEL IN THE HOSE THAT SPILLED ONTO THE DOCK. A VERY SMALL AMOUNT HIT THE WATER. THEY CONTAINED WITH BOOMS AND USED ABSORBENT PADS TO CLEAN UP THE FUEL IN THE WATER.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED THAT HE SHOULD HAVE ADDED THE HOSE ON THE VESSEL SIDE AND THIS WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED. WE NOW INCLUDE THIS POINT IN OUR USCG PERSON IN CHARGE TRAINING.

column168: LOADING OF 55-GAL, STEEL DRUMS ONTO THE TRANSPORTER VEHICLE (BOX TRUCK) IS DONE USING A FORKLIFT EQUIPPED WITH A DRUM CLAMP. DURING THE LOADING OF THE DRUMS TO THE TRUCK, ONE DRUM SLIPPED FROM THE CLAMP AND HIT THE GROUND DENTING THE LID AND THE SIDE OF THE DRUM (FAILURE 511). THE LID AND THE LIP OF THE DRUM USED TO SECURE THE LID WERE DENTED/CRUSHED AND THE CONTENTS WERE ABLE TO LEAK OUT FAILURE 109, 305, AND 312). IN THE SHORT TIME (LESS THAN 2 MINUTES) IT TOOK THE OPERATOR TO DISENGAGE FROM THE FORKLIFT AND LIFT THE DRUM UPRIGHT FROM ITS SIDE TO PREVENT MORE OF THE CONTENTS FROM SPILLING FROM THE DAMAGED LID. BASED ON THE VOLUME OF THE CONTENTS REMAINING IN THE DRUM, IT WAS ESTIMATED THE QUANTITY TO HAVE SPILLED WAS APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS.  IMMEDIATELY THE OPERATOR CALLED ON HIS RADIO FOR ASSISTANCE. SPILL KITS ARE READILY AVAILABLE AT THE DRUM STORAGE AREA AND HE WAS ABLE TO OBTAIN THESE BOOMS AND ADSORBENT PADS TO CONTAIN AND PREVENT THE SPILL FROM EXPANDING. ADDITIONAL EMPLOYEES BECAME AVAILABLE FOR ASSISTING IN THE CLEANUP. THE AREA THE SPILL OCCURRED WAS CONCRETE WITH DIRT AT THE EDGES. THE WASTE SOLVENT HAS A SHEEN AND WAS EASILY IDENTIFIED FOR CLEANUP. ANY AFFECTED DIRT WAS REMOVED USING A TRACK-HOE AND PLACED INTO 55-GAL STEEL DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL AS HAZARDOUS WASTE. USED ADSORBENT AND BOOMS WERE ALSO DRUMMED FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL. THE REMAINING CONTENTS IN THE DAMAGED DRUM WERE TRANSFERRED TO ANTOHER 55-GAL STEEL DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: ASSESSING LOADING AREA FOR ADDITIONAL CONTAINMENT IF POSSIBLE TO INCREASE THE CONTAINMENT WITHOUT ADDING ISSUES FOR FORKLIFT ACCESS.  ASSESSING WHETHER A TANK VS. DRUMS FOR WASTE SOLVENT STORAGE IS VIABLE FOR DISPOSAL.  CONTINUE FORKLIFT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TRAINING WITH EMPLOYEES.

column168: 1) HOSES WERE CONNECTED TO THE EMPTY ROAD TANKER (130) AND THE CUSTOMER’S FULL CONTAINER OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. 2) VACUUM PUMP WAS STARTED BY THE DRIVER AND THE CUSTOMER VALVE OPENED BY A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE CUSTOMER.  3) THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SAW PRODUCT SPRAYING FROM THE HOSE CONNECTIONS. column168: Original comments:  Package was found in the unload during the outbound shift. Package contained a gallon bottle leaking corrosive liquid. The bottle appeared to leak approximatelyone tenth of a liquid ounce on the upper side of the package.  New Comments: This late entry is from my prior mistake before where the same thing happened. I fixed the incident, so I thought until I received an E-mail from Stephanie. Then I went and found the package in the cage, I missed it from before because my labeling was off. Not an excuse. It was my fault and I take full responsibility for it. It was just a difficult week as I took on a large portion of work, which isnt a problem besides the fact I am part-time. It will not happen again. My course of action for future prevention I have already been working on as I have been trying to step up more so and process damaged HazMats. My fellow co-worker Keith Rugar has helped me with learning/remembering these processes. I sincerely apologize and will keep on practicing to avoid future mistakes.

column58: Manway or Dome Cover; Tank Shell
column168: DRIVER BILL SCHNEIDER WAS DRIVING AT 45 MPH EB/NB AROUND A WIDE LEFT-HAND CURVE ON MT-213 LEAVING CUT BANK, MT. THE TRUCK AND DOUBLE TRAILERS BEGAN TO SLIDE ON THE SLUSH TOWARD THE OUTSIDE OF THE CURVE. BILL WAS ABLE TO KEEP THE COMBINATION ON THE SHOULDER FOR SEVERAL SECONDS BEFORE THE PUP LEFT THE PAVEMENT AND STRUCK A CULVERT AT ABOUT 40 MPH. IT LOST A WHEEL, WENT AIRBORNE, CLIPPED A POWER POLE, SHEARED ANOTHER, AND OVERTURNED. THIS PULLED THE LEAD TRAILER AND TRACTOR OVER ONTO THEIR RIGHT SIDES. THE COMBINATION STRUCK A FENCE AND A VEHICLE IN THE PARKING LOT OF GLACIER ELECTRIC COOPERATIVE BESIDE THE ROAD, DOING DAMAGE TO BOTH. IT APPEARS THAT ONE OF THE FENCE POLES CAUSED A PUNCTURE IN THE SHELL OF THE PUP (APPROXIMATELY 3 INCH DIAMETER ON THE LEFT SIDE), BUT THE TRAILER LANDED WITH THAT SIDE UP, AND VERY LITTLE PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THIS HOLE. THERE WERE SLOW LEAKS OF GASOLINE AND DIESEL FROM THE MANWAY HATCHES ON THE TOPS OF BOTH TRAILERS. EMPLOYEES OF GLAICER AND THE NEARBY CHS PIPELINE FACILITY REACTED VERY QUICKLY TO CONTAIN THE SPILL BY CATCHING FUEL IN BUCKETS AND TRANSFERRING IT TO A PORTABLE TANK, AS WELL AS DIKING THE DRAINAGE DITCH BESIDE THE ROAD AND USING SORBENTS TO MINIMIZE THE SPREAD OF THE FREE PRODUCT. THE TRAILERS WERE DRAINED OF PRODUCT , AND THE COMBINATION WAS SEPARATED, RIGHTED, AND TOWED. THE RECOVERED PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CUSTOMER. AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, THE DITCH DIKE AND BOOMS WERE LEFT IN PLACE TO PREVENT CONTAMINATED MELTWATER FROM MOVING TOWARD THE INTERMITTENT STEAM BED 150 YARDS TO THE NORTH. THE TRAILERS ORIGINALLY CONTAINED 3,001 GALLONS OF 87E10 GASOLINE AND 9,000 GALLONS OF #2 DYED DIESEL FUEL. ALL OF THIS FUEL WAS RECOVERED WITH THE EXCEPTION OF 24 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND 214 GALLONS OF DIESEL. WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS HEADED UP THE CLEANUP EFFORTS. WITH THE SPRING MELT, THE GROUND ON SITE IS NOW EXPOSED. WCEC PROJECT MANAGER NATHAN OLSEN WAS ABLE TO OBSERVE THE SOIL CONDITIONS THIS WEEK. HE IS CURRENTLY CONDUCTING SOIL TESTING AND PLANNING FOR SMALL AMOUNT OF EXCAVATION TO REMEDIATE THE AFFECTED SOIL.
column169: THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THIS RELEASE WAS EXCESSIVE SPEED FOR THE WORSENING ROAD CONDITIONS AT THE TIME OF THE OVERTURN. THE DRIVER WAS SIMPLY DRIVING TOO FAST IN THE WINTRY MIX THAT WAS ON THE ROAD, AND THE DRIVER NEEDS TO SLOW DOWN IN SUCH CONDITIONS. THERE WAS A CONTRIBUTING CIRCUMSTANCE WITH THE TRAILERS. IN THE SLICK ROAD CONDITIONS, THE DRIVER COULD HAVE REDUCED THE CHANCES OF THE INCIDENT BY REDUCING THE LOAD AND RUNNING WITHOUT THE PUP TRAILER. WE HAVE EMPHASIZED TO THE DRIVERS THAT THEY HAVE THE AUTHORITY AND RESPONSIBILITY TO DROP THE PUP IN SUCH CONDITIONS. THERE WAS AN ADDITIONAL CONTRIBUTING MECHANICAL FACTOR. DUE TO WORK BEING DONE ON THE LEAD TRAILER THAT BILL NORMALLY WOULD HAVE BEEN DRIVING, HE WAS OPERATING A DIFFERENT TRAILER, WITHOUT A PERMANENTLY LUBRICATED FOR SUBSTITUTED TRAILER. THIS LIKELY RESULTED IN LESS STEERING CONTROL DUE TO THE ADDITIONAL FRICTION BETWEEN THE FIFTH WHEEL AND THE APRON. DRIVERS WITH SIMILAR TRAILERS HAVE BEEN REMINDED TO ADD LUBRICATION FOR THE FIFTH WHEEL WHEN THEY CHANGE TRAILERS.

column168: A MECHANICAL FAILURE ON DELIVERY TRUCK 137 CAUSED FUEL TO LEAK FROM THE AIR ELIMINATOR TUBE IN THE REAR OF THE FUEL TRUCK OVER THE DISTANCE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE. THIS TRUCK INITIALLY HAD TWO PUMPS IN THE REAR AND DID NOT NEED THE SECONDARY PUMP SO ONE WAS REMOVED. WHEN ONE OF THE PUMPS WAS REMOVED THE AIR ELIMINATOR HOSE GOING FORM THAT PUMP WAS NO LONGER CONNECTED TO ANYTHING SO A CAP WAS PUT ON THE END OF IT TO KEEP ANY FUEL FROM RUNNING OUT. WHILE THE DRIVER WAS ASCENDING A STEEP HILL THAT CAP FELL OUT AND FUEL WAS ABLE TO FLOW OUT OF THE AIR ELIMINATOR HOSE WHEN THE FUEL SURGED TO THE TOP OF THE COMPARTMENT INTERNALLY. THE AMOUNT SPILLED IS ESTIMATED TO BE BETWEEN 20 AND 30 GALLONS.
column169: AT ANY POINT WHEN AN ALTERATION IS MADE TO A PUMP OR HOSE LINE THAT COULD RELEASE FUEL A CAP MUST BE WELDED ON WHERE POSSIBLE, THIS WILL ELIMINATE THE CHANCE OF A PLASTIC CAP WEARING OUT AND FALLING OFF.

column168: ON FRIDAY MARCH 23RD, PENN TANK LINES COMPANY DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND IN THE #1 LANE, I-95 AT EXIT 16 WHICH IS NEAR PEMBROKE PINES, FL. A VEHICLE VEERED INTO THE #1 LANE STRIKING THE TRACTOR TRAILER, FORCING THE OUR UNIT OFF THE ROAD AND THE UNIT FLIPPED ON IT SIDE. POLICE AND FIRE CREWED CALLED, CLIFF BERRY ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED. SOURCE REMOVAL WORK WAS DONE, HOWEVER THE LANDFILL CLOSED AT 12:30 SO THERE WASN’T A PLACE TO TAKE THE SOURCE MATERIAL. THE LANDFILL IS NOT OPEN ON SUNDAY. CBI WSA ON SITE WITH EQUIPMENT AT 07:00. CONES WERE IN PLACE, JORGESON ARRIVED PREPARED FOR LANE CLOSURE AT 08:00. PLASTIC WAS REMOVED FROM THE IMPACTED AREA AND SOURCE REMOVAL COMMENCED SHORTLY AFTER 07:00 FROM THE SOUTHERN EXTENT OF IMPACT. IMPACT WAS ENCOUNTERED TO 3 FEET IN THE SOUTHERN END, THE WATER TABLE IS JUST BENEATH THAT. DUE TO THE AREA CONSTRAINTS, SOIL HAD TO BE REMOVED WITH AN EXCAVATOR AND LOADED INTO A LOADER BUCKET. WHEN FULL, THE LOADER RAN FROM THE SOURCE AREA TO THE TRUCKS WHICH WERE LOCATED SOUTH OF THE GUARDRAIL. CBI WAS ABLE TO LOAD 2 TRUCKS PRIOR TO LANDFILL CLOSURE.  NEAR THE END OF THE MORNING, AS SOURCE REMOVAL MOVED NORTH, SOME OF THE LOST 2,000 GALLONS IN THE FORM OF PRODUCT BECAME EVIDENT, SEEPING UP OUT OF THE LIMESTONE EXCAVATION BASE. THE IMPACTED AREA IS APPROXIMATELY 20 FEET OFF THE ROADWAY. SOURCE REMOVAL HAS PROCEEDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH FAC 62-780.
column169: REVIEW THIS INCIDENT WITH EMPLOYEES (DRIVERS, TRAINERS, SUPERVISORS, AND MANAGERS). FOCUS ON RISK/SAFETY MEETINGS ON THIS INCIDENT WITH ALL DRIVERS.

column168: At 05:23 ET, ERTS received a call from Efrain Corpuz with XPO Logistics Terminal LSX. The caller reported that in (1) cardboard box containing (4) 1 gallon metal pails of UN1133 Uni-Thane Polyurethane Sealant, approximately 2 gallons spilled into the box and onto the trailer floor of trailer #3157352 (in bound from LHW) due to improper loading. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller regarding the material hazards, and ERTS instructed the caller to utilize safety glasses and safety gloves to containerize the impacted absorbents / debris into (1) 10 gallon metal drum. ERTS to generate Titan and provide SDS. Spills in trailers, concrete docks, containment areas, inside buildings are not into environment and not considered reportable. A DOT 5800 will be required for this incident due to the packing group II classification.

On March 06, 2018 at 1850 ET, Earl Coggins with Landstar called ERTS in regards to a release located at a Hougoton, TX. The caller stated that during unloading operations the driver and consignee noticed that a (1) 330-gallon tote containing UN1760 Herbicide "Gramoxone" released from a loose cap. Approximately 3-gallons of trailer floor which is already dried up and contained with absorbents. No waterways, soils, or drains were reported to have been impacted at this time. The caller requested that ERTS send a team for tomorrow morning during straight time. At 1930 ET, ERTS dispatched Talon LPE who will be on scene by 0900 ET tomorrow morning. A DOT5800 report is required for this incident. At this time, no other regulatory reporting is required. At 1926 ET, ERTS called the driver who stated stated that he has not yet called Chemtrec but will call as soon as he can. He also stated that he will send photos of the BOL to ERTS shortly.     1320 ET on 3.7.18, The contractor confirmed that they arrived on scene at about 1250 ET. They confirmed that approximately 2-gallons released to a 10 x 8 ft area on the trailer floor and appears to have splashed on some of the walls during transit. They are currently applying fresh absorbents and adding water to the dried release in order to remove the material from the impacted surfaces. Photos have been requested.

column168: At 0600 hrs., The WLE Brewster Yard Car Inspector, while inspecting an inbound train, noticed a loud hissing noise coming from car UTLX 309792.  He called the Brewster Yard Master who then called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for Wheeling and Lake Erie.  When I came out to inspect the car, I took off seal number 0018798.  After I opened the Housing Lid, I noticed the vapor valve leaking badly.  You could actually hear the leak from 3 car lengths away.  I tried to tighten the valve handle to see if it was loose and it was.  After I tightened the handle, the leak stopped.  The valve plug was not even hand tight. I tool tightened the valve plug.  I them installed seal number 971782 on the housing lid and then released the car for service.    NARRI:  5(4+5) x 2=47                     Cause Code: 379,390
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: First of all we have to clarify we work in the GOV warehouse where our actions are limited since any action requires a Customs authorization. During breakdown process of flt 215 (LAXGRU) we were informed by the GOV and AA agents (Tristar) there was a container AKE.79122.AA smelling an unusual odor when unit was opened they realized a mixed shipments into unit where all were removed except the volume smelling the unusual odor. Immediately the container was moved to other area having been isolated from the line and banded with warning straps around it. It was realized a small quantity of the liquid had been spilled inside the container and the reason was a small crack in the closure (cap) of the package. We were called by GOV agents to present the documentation, however, we had AWB only with description...ACETOPHENONE...We think better to issue a SDS and ERG page to present to them. The volume was moved and kept in DG area until date. GOV is going to provide the pictures via site once we do not have authorization from Customs to get it as we should.

column168: Tractor / Trailer (tanker), was traveling on Murphy in Belton, SC. The vehicle ran off the right side of the roadway into a ditch and laid on its side. The product from tanker was pumped out before uprighting the unit and onsite environmental company cleaned up the spilled diesel from saddle tank. The roadway was blocked from the time of the accident until approximately 14:50 hours.
column169: This incident was due to driver error. However, changes have been made to avoid smaller roads (such as Murphy Road) around the terminals in the immediate area.

column168: When transferring a loaded IBC box from a truck to the storage facility for the purposes of consolidation, the forklift operator discovered the IBC had developed a leak on the bottom underside of the container. The forklift operator stopped work, and called in a response team. The response crew, wearing the correct personal protective equipment, transferred this paint related material to a new IBC container. The damaged IBC and the waste generated from the cleanup were placed in the appropriate branch waste stream.     It was discovered that the damaged IBC had been improperly prepared for transport by the generator; the package was missing the rigid fiberboard floor, and thus the bottom outer bag was not supported and had sagged through the gaps in the pallet. These sagged areas were punctured by the forklift blades when the operator moved this IBC. In addition, it was discovered that the generator had not stacked and secured the inner paint cans in this IBC correctly, which led to the IBC having loose liquid paint inside.     This was reported to the CT DEEP, Spill #2018-0808.
column169: When introduced into transportation, this package showed no evidence of a release. The generator has been contacted and asked to retrain its staff on the correct preparation of this type of IBC package for transportation, with an emphasis on correctly assembling and loading IBC's with paint related materials.

PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: ON OR ABOUT MARCH 5, 2018 OUR BUSINESS GLOBAL PARTS INC SHIPPED AN AIRCRAFT FIRE BOTTLE WE ARE WRITING TO SELF-DISCLOSE A POTENTIAL VIOLATION OF THE UNITED STATES HAZARDOUS MATERIALS  REGULATIONS.  GLOBAL  PARTS INC IS A DISTRIBUTOR OF AIRCRAFT PARTS.   THE UNIT IN QUESTION WAS A FIRE BOTTLE MEANT FOR INSTALLATION IN AN AIRCRAFT PROPER SHIPPING NAME FIRE EXTINGUISHER THE BOTTLE NORMALLY INCLUDES AN ACTUATING SQUIB WAS REMOVED FOR TRANSPORTATION.   THE UNIT WAS SHIPPED TO PACIFIC SCIENTIFIC WHICH IS THE MANUFACTURER OF THE UNIT TO BE OVERHAULED THE PACIFIC SCIENTIFIC FACILITY IS LOCATED IN MIAMI FLORIDA. WE BELIEVE THAT THIS MAY MEET THE DEFINITION OF REVERSE LOGISTICS DESCRIBED IN 49 CFR 171.8 BUT IT WOULD NOT MEET THE LIMITED QUANTITY REQUIREMENTS FOR USING REVERSE LOGISTICS DESCRIBED IN 49 CFR 173.157   THE UNIT WAS SHIPPED  BY GROUND TRANSPORTATION VIA FEDEX GROUND THE UNIT INCLUDES A PACKAGING BEARING THE CODE DOT SPEC E7945 THE UNIT WAS PACKAGED IN A STRONG OUTER PACKAGING IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CF
column169: WE PERFORMED A ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS IN ORDER TO MORE ACCURATELY IDENTIFY APPROPRIATE  CASUAL FACTORS INCLUDED:  1. THE ARTICLE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH AS A CORE THROUGH THE SYSTEM FOR  MAINTENANCE  EVALUATION CORES TYPICALLY ARE ACCEPTED UNPRESSURIZED AND ARE THEREFORE EXPECTED TO ARRIVE  UNPRESSURIZED. THIS LEAD TO A MISTAKEN EXPECTATION FOR THE ARTICLE TO BE IN AN UNCHARGED UNPRESSURIZED CONDITION  2.  NO EXISTING CHECK LIST AT THIS STATION TO HELP IDENTIFY STATES THAT MAY REASONABLY RESULT IN HAZMAT SHIPMENTS  IDENTIFICATION.       CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS IDENTIFIED BASED ON THE CASUAL FACTORS AND IS BEING IMPLEMENTED.    1. CONTAINMENT ACTION WAS IDENTIFIED BASED ON THE CAUSAL FACTORS AND IS BEING IMPLEMENTED CONTAINMENT VIA COMPLETED OJT TRAINING REGARDING NEED FOR IDENTIFYING AND CONFIRMING STATUS  OF POTENTIAL HAZMAT ARTICLES FOR PROPER  DETERMINATION OF SHIPPING / HANDLING NEEDS. TRAINING PROVIDED TO ALL TRAINED HAZMAT EMPLOYEES TRAINING IS DOCUMENTED  AND DOCUMENTATION IS ADDED TO EMPLOYEE TRAINING RECORDS  2. DEVELOPMENT OF CHECKLIST FOR SHIPPING TEAMS REGARDING HAZMAT IDENTIFICATION TRAINING FOR APPLICABLE PERSONNEL ON THE CHECKLIST  3. ALL SHIPPERS WILL BE TRAINED  THAT THE ERP SYSTEM IS FOR REFERENCE ONLY AND THAT AN UNFLAGGED ITEM MUST STILL BE CHECKED INDEPENDENTLY FOR HAZMAT STATUS  4. ADDITION OF ALL DEVELOPED TRAINING TO THE QUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM TRAINING DATABASE AS RECURRENT TRAINING.

column168: A facility forklift operator, while loading a pallet onto a vehicle for transport to a final waste destination, pushed a pallet forward while trying to lift it, which caused the pallet to make contact with and puncture a drum positioned behind the pallet on the floor of the trailer. This release occurred in a trailer; no ground, soil, or water sources were impacted. The facility quickly deployed  an emergency response crew wearing the correct personal protective equipment, who over packed the drum into a suitable UN rated salvage overpack  drum, and cleaned the area completely. All waste generated from this cleanup was also placed into this overpack drum. This drum then continued to its  intended final destination without further incident.    This was reported to the state of Connecticut; CT DEEP #2018-01302 Operator #205
column169: The forklift operator was not allowed to operate a forklift again until he received additional forklift training. He was asked in particular to maintain  greater situational awareness, to slow down, and not rush. The operator will receive close supervision and observation for a period of time to make sure his forklift technique improves.

Kingsport Fire and American Environmental were dispatched to scene immediately.  Product entered storm drain but was contained immediately by KFD and American Environmental.  Remediation began immediately by American Environmental.  Product was contained and vacuumed out of drain and off concrete.  Excavation was performed to remove contaminated soil.  Clean soil was top filled onto excavated area.

column168: On 3/8/18, the UTLX 12244 was inspected by a CPUC Hazmat Inspector in Barstow, CA yard.  The inspector noted an odor and heard audible hissing coming from the car.  It was observed that the manway ears appeared to have been bent downward by overtorquing the manway swingbolts.  This condition did not allow the hard gasket to fully seal the nozzle to lid surface resulting in a minor vapor release.  BNSF Hazmat responder arrived to inspect the car and replaced the manway gasket with a soft elastomeric nozzle gasket to allow for adequate sealing.  The car owner (Nutrien) then arranged for an OTMA to continue travel to the diverted destination for repairs.  There were no injuries or exposures associated with this response.  Estimated release volumes are entirely estimated as it is not possible to determine an actual release volume of vapor from the container.
column169: Verdegaal indicated that they do not utilize the manway as part of their unloading process.  Although the appurtenance may not be used, the shipper is responsible for all components on the car prior to releasing in transportation.  Shipper should follow up with unloading personnel and review procedures for releasing cars back into transportation.

column168: BNSF Mechanical employees report an odor associated with the UTLX 78791 while the car was spotted on the RIP track in Barstow, CA on 3/10/18 at approximately 11:06 CT.  The area around the car was isolated and a BNSF Hazmat Employee inspected the car.  During the inspection, the responder found all of the manway swing bolts were less than tool tight with a number of them that were less than finger tight.  The manway was opened for inspection and the gasket was replaced.  The responder secured the manway swing bolts to a tool tight condition and released the car for continued transportation.  Only a minor amount of liquid spillage occurred near the nozzle, the leaked vapor dissipated by natural ventilation.  Once secured, the car was released to continue in transportation.
column169: The shipper should review procedures with loading personnel to ensure that they understand the proper procedures for manway cover securement and post loading inspections are thorough enough to correct items such as this before the car enters transportation.

column168: On 03/10/2018, RL 166 was reported leaking upon deramp at BNSF San Bernardino. The waybill lists that the unit was carrying hazardous material. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and moved to the containment pit. R L Carriers was contacted and hired United Pumping to inspect the load. Cargo revealed a load of mixed freight, with a partial second layer, to include palletized shrink rapped boxes with no cargo securement. The source of the leak was a crushed 1 gallon pale of UN1263 paint related material  (hazardous) located on the first layer, in the middle of the load, with no other cargo on top of the pallet. The weight of the upper boxes within the pallet caused the pale to be crushed. The box of (4) 1 gallon pales was found on the bottom of the pallet and 1 pale was completely emptied for a total of one  gallon of leaked material.  The unit was remediated by United Pumping and holds have been released so that the unit can outgate.
column169: Shipper has been notified by LARS.  The shipper should have properly applied blocking and bracing of trailer contents to prevent shifting of the load. Review with personnel responsible for loading and securing the container.

column168: Driver was entering I-40 on-ramp (westbound) from Sunnylane when he noticed product leaking from the rear of the trailer.  When it was safe to do so, the driver pulled over and discovered product leaking from between the trailer axles. Emergency stop handle was pulled with no stoppage of leaking product. At that time, the driver was not aware of storm drain under the trailer when he parked. Emergency services notified, FD arrived on scene and placed catch basin under the trailer. Another unit was dispatched to the scene to pump off the product, stopping the leak. It was discovered the next day that the seal for the belly valve was comprised allowing the product to go into the wet lines. The seal on the coupling for the wet line to the belly valve gave way, allowing the product to be discharged. It was determined that 55 gallons of E-10 gasoline leaked out. An environmental company was dispatched to the scene for remediation.
column169: All belly valves and coupling gaskets where removed from this trailer and replaced with new.

column168: FOLLOWING AND INVESTIGATION, IT WAS REVEALED THAT THE “THERMAL RELIEF MOTIVE GAS SUPPLY MAINTENANCE VALVE” HAD BEEN INADVERTENTLY CLOSED ON THE LOWER LEFT TANK. THIS MAINTENANCE VALVE IS THE ONLY SUPPLY TO THE THERMAL RELIEF SYSTEM. OVER TIME, THE NOW-ISOLATED ACTUATION SYSTEM BLED DOWN IN PRESSURE AND ALLOWED THE THERMAL RELIEF ACTUATORS ON ALL FOUR CYLINDERS TO OPEN. THE OPENING OF THE THERMAL RELIEF ACTUATORS OF ALL FOUR CYLINDERS RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF NATURAL GAS TO THE ATMOSPHERE. THREE OF THE FOUR CYLINDERS COMPLETELY VENTED DOWN TO ATMOSPHERIC PRESSURE. HOWEVER, DUE TO THE PROBABLE SLOW-OPENING OF THE LOWER LEFT CYLINDER, IT IS SUSPECTED THAT SOME OIL THAT WAS IN THE LINE, WAS COOLED AND FROZEN BY THE FLOWING GAS FROM THE “CRACKED OPEN” VALVE. THIS ALLOWED A “FREEZE-PLUG” OF ICE TO FORM IN THE VENT LINE OF THIS CYLINDER, PREVENTING COMPLETE VENTING OF THE CYLINDER. FROM OUTWARD APPEARANCE, YOU WOULD ASSUME THAT THE TRAILER WOULD HAVE FULLY VENTED ALL 4 CYLINDERS, BECAUSE BY THE TIME OF XNG PERSONNEL ARRIVAL ON-SITE, ALL 4 THERMAL RELIEF ACTUATORS WERE FULLY OPEN…

column168: Carrier at shipper having CTMV loaded, shipper employee informed carrier to shut the internal and external valve. Shipper shut off the loading system. Product spilling from the external valve through the cap. Carrier found the external valve cap had no gasket and the internal valve was open. Duration of release 20 minutes.     event 68378

The driver was pumping off into customer (Penske) ASTs. The driver had obtained veeder root reading and determined there was room in the tanks for the load to fit prior to unloading. During pump off, the north AST tank overfilled resulting in a spill of est. 700 gallons. Product ran under tanks and moved downhill across the parking lot then left the parking lot and entered bar ditch. The driver shut down pumping process and started containing product spilled. After the fact, it was discovered that veeder root system on tanks was inaccurate.  Also, the driver is not responsible for customer piping/valve alignment, when offloading product was only going into the north tank. The tank did not equalize.
column169: Communicate to customers and or owners of tanks, drivers are/will not adjust or make valve change alignments to customer tanks. Customers need to have a person of working knowledge of how their system works present when offloading.

column168: A driver was preparing to leave the Veolia 10 day in-transit facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI with a loaded semi-van trailer when he observed a drip from the front of the trailer. The trailer was placed into containment and unloaded to get at the leaking drum which was located in the nose of the van. It is estimated that approximately 1 gallon of the material was released within the van and containment. The drum leak originated from a slight scratch in the bottom of the 55-gallon metal drum. The drum was placed into a salvage container along with the oil dry from cleaning up the spill. All containers were then loaded onto a second trailer for continued transportation.
column169: This incident was reviewed with Veolia personnel to remind all to review container integrity prior to placing containers in transportation. In this case, the container was received from another transporter.  It is unclear how, when or where the damage to the drum occurred.

column168: While a Veolia driver was attempting to load a roll-off box containing paint related material at the 10-day in transit facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI. As he was loading the roll-off box onto the trailer, he noticed some liquid leaking from the rear door. He immediately set the box back onto the asphalt and began to contain and clean up the spilled liquid. The liquid may have been rainwater that had collected in the roll-off box. The investigation revealed that the rear door of the roll-off box had not been properly tightened.
column169: This incident will be reviewed with all employees who use roll-off boxes to ensure materials that are being placed in the boxes are properly packaged. In addition, we will review the procedure to ensure the openings are properly tightened prior to being placed into the transportation phase.

column168: Original comments:   We received one gallon of Zep door san disinfectant (one gallon.) This container had a loose cap and leaked saturating this package. We quickly isolated this package and were able to contain all of the liquid.    New Comments:

Original comments:   PACKAGE WAS FOUND LOADED TO A VAN BY A DRIVER. THE DRIVER BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO MY ATTENTION AND I DEALT WITH IT ACCORDINGLY. THE EXTERIOR OF THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND DAMP ALONG ONE SIDE AND PART OF THE BOTTOM. THE PACKAGE SEEMS TO HAVE BEEN INSPECTED AT SOME POINT PRIOR TO THIS BECAUSE THE TOP AND THE BOTTOM CLOSURES HAD BEEN HAPHAZARDLY RETAPED AND THE ORIGINAL BARCODE HAD BEEN SLICED THROUGH ON TOP.  UPON INSPECTION, THERE WAS NO PACKING MATERIAL SURROUNDING THE FOUR PLASTIC CONTAINERS.  ALL FOUR CONTAINERS WERE PACKED TWICE IN PLASTIC, INDIVIDUALLY SEALED BAGS AND PLACED INTO A LARGER PLASTIC BAG.  TWO OF THE FOUR CONTAINERS WERE FOUND TO HAVE LOOSE CAPS, CAUSING THE INNER LIQUID TO SEEP OUT WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS HANDLED. DUE TO THE MANY LAYERS OF PLASTIC, THE LEAKAGE WAS MINIMAL. Original comments:   Undeclared Hazmat Shipment. Package had very limited amount of hazmat identifiers. Package was not identified and was sent up the conveyor system. Package was tipped on the conveyor and the bottle with the loose cap had some of its contents leak out. Package was stopped and removed from belt at the sortation tower. Package was on conveyor belt for approx. 30 seconds. After package was removed from the belt QA was contacted. QA personnel put on protective equipment and placed the package inside of a tote to minimize any further spilling. No one came into contact with the liquid. Advised the package handler who removed it from the tower to thoroughly wash hands as a precautionary measure. Once QA established that the leakage was from a loose cap, the caps were tightened and the tote was moved tothe QA are to be processed.  Advised the unload manager to have package handlers treat any package with hazmat markings or any other possible hazmat identifiers as hazmats to reduce the chance of undeclared Hazmats being sent through the conveyor system.    New Comments:
Original comments:  Im not sure if it was water damage from the rain or if the caps were loose.  New Comments:

It was reported that approximately 20 gallons released from an in-ground storage tank due to a fuel overfill during offloading operations. The release impacted the concrete and a storm drain. Dupre Logistics on-site personnel stated that when they were filling an in-ground tank from an oil tanker at a service station they overfilled the tank, spilling an estimated 20 gallons that traveled down the concrete area and into a storm drain. Dupre personnel stated that they placed absorbent pads on the concrete in order to contain the gasoline spill. No further information was given. ERTS notified the NRC (1206177) and the state Texas Spill Reporting Hotline (20180907).
column169: Truck driver is to not overfill the tank when refueling.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF FIVE 330 GALLON TOTES OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE TO OUR CUSTOMER, MAHONING COUNTY SANITARY ENGINEERS IN MINERAL RIDGE, OHIO. THE TOTES ARE MOVED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WITH AN ELECTRICAL PALLET JACK AND THE CUSTOMER, USING A FORKLIFT AT GROUND LEVEL, THEN PICKS UP THE TOTES AND PLACES THEM INTO THEIR STORAGE AREA. THE BED OF THE TRAILER, A 2011 PETERBILT STRAIGHT TRUCK, IS CONSTRUCTED OF DIAMOND PLATING AND OVER TIME, THE FLOOR HAS STARTED TO RIPPLE, CREATING SMALL ‘PEAKS’ AND ‘VALLEYS’ IN THE FLOORING. THE DRIVER WAS MANEUVERING THE THIRD TOTE IN POSITION WHEN THE WHEELS OF THE PALLET JACK STOPPED IN THE LAST ‘VALLEY’ CLOSET TO THE REAR OF THE TRUCK. IN AN EFFORT TO GET THE PALLET JACK MOVING, THE DRIVER SLIGHTLY ‘FEATHERED’ THE ACCELERATOR ON THE PALLET JACK AND WHEN THE PALLET JACK BEGAN MOVING AGAIN, THE FORKS BOTTOMED OUT ON THE FLOORING. THE PALLET JACK CAME TO A STOP AND THE TOTE, ALREADY CLOSE TO THE END OF THE TRUCK, CONTINUED TO MOVE, SLIDING OFF THE FORKS OF THE PALLET JACK AND OUT ONTO THE GROUND WHERE IT BROKE AND RELEASED ALL 330 GALLONS OF CAUSTIC OUT ONTO THE GROUND. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY BOTH FACILITY PERSONNEL AND AN OUTSIDE REMEDIATION COMPANY,
column169: SINCE THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED, A NEW DIAMOND PLATE FLOOR HAS BEEN INSTALLED OVER THE CURRENT FLOOR OF THIS STRAIGHT TRUCK, RESULTING IN A CONSISTENTLY LEVEL FLOOR FROM FRONT TO BACK. HAD IT NOT BEEN FOR THE RIPPLES IN THE FLOORING, THIS INCIDENT WOULD NOT HAVE TAKEN PLACE AND THE NEW FLOORING ELIMINATES THE POSSIBILITY THAT THIS INCIDENT WILL OCCUR AGAIN AS A DIRECT RESULT OF UNEVEN FLOORING.

column168: our driver was traveling on I-10 in Houston when a passenger vehicle cut him off causing him to have a hard break event. One IBC container fell over on the trailer. The hard breaking caused the load to shift forward loosening the cargo straps on the flatbed being hauled. When the container fell the product began to leak out around the cap.The driver called into Safety immediately to report the incident at approximately 1400 on 9 March 2018. Safety directed him to use his spill kit to contain the spill. After Safety confirmed what product was released he called Hazmat One to dispatch hazmat recovery team. The container was stood back up and the Hydrochloric was neutralized and the load was secured. Approximately 50 gallons was released. The chemical spill was contained to the trailer and the roadway.
column169: The driver was instructed on proper securement procedures and it was recommended to the customer to utilized bracing in the floor to prevent the load from shifting forward.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED PACKAGE WAS NOT STOPPED IN BURA LIKE ONE OF THE OTHER PACKAGES IN THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS TURNED IN TO THE FAA THERE, AND IT MOVED ON TO LAXR BY TRUCK. BURA HAD CONTACTED LAXR TO INFORM THEM THAT IT WAS PROBABLY UNDECLARED AS WELL, AND WAS STOPPED AND HELD ON 2-15-2018. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT LEAKING. LAXR FAILED TO CONTACT OUR DG ADMIN OFFICE THAT THEY WERE HOLDING THIS ADDITIONAL PACKAGE AND NOT UNTIL I CONTACTED THE FAA ON 3-16-2018, THE FAA DID NOT KNOW IT WAS THERE. I SUBMITTED AN UNDECLARED REPORT AT 08:15 (CDT) 2018 ON 3-16-2018 TO REPORT THE PACKAGE SO THEY COULD INSPECT IT AS WELL. I WAS LATER TOLD BY STEVEN REDEKER THAT IT COULD BE RELEASED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: AT 8:29 HRS ON 3/1/18 TANK CAR GATX 1213 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE DONE AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY KSC SHREVEPORT LA YARD.  THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT ADDITIONALLY AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DEPLOYED TO ASSIST WITH THE RESPONSE.    THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND PRESSURE RELIEVED FROM THE CAR TO STOP THE LEAK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS EMANATING FROM THE LIQUID  VALVE FOUR BOLT FLANGE  THE ROOT CAUSE WAS A DETECTIVE FLANGE GASKET THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE WERE TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT AL PRODUCT WAS CLEANED FROM THE CAR AND COLLECTED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL ONCE COMPLETED THE SHIPPER APPLIED FOR AND WAS GRANTED AN OTMA-1 SO THE CAR COULD RETURN TO TRANSPORTATION.     FILE NOTE ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A BULK SHIPMENT AKA ONE CAR LOAD THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED  IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER DOES  NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTITY THIS VALUE

column168: THE EXTERNAL VALVE, FOR DHDU 127355-0 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING YARD INSPECTION AT THE CP BENSENVILLE INTERMODAL YARD ON 3-2-18 AT APPROXIMATELY 09:32. THE YARD WAS EVACUATED, AND TRAFFIC WAS RESTRICTED ON THE ADJOINING ROAD, DUE TO THE UNKNOWN MAGNITUDE OF THE RELEASE.  A QUALIFIED ER CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO SITE, AND AIR MONITORING EQUIPMENT WAS USED TO ESTABLISHED THAT NO ELEVATED LEVELS OF PYRIDINE WERE FOUND IN THE AREA. THE CONTRACTOR SUBSEQUENTLY FOUND THAT THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND CAPS WERE LOOSE. THE CAP AND VALVE WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE INTERNAL VAVLE WAS FOUND TO BE INTERSTATIAL PIPING BETWEEN THE INNER AND OUTER VALVES. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP, AND PLACED INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THE UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.  THE PACKAGE RECEIVED WAS THE SAME BOX WE HAD ORIGINALLY SENT OUT WITH THE UNIT CONTAINING THE LITHIUM BATTERY. THIS BOX ORIGINALLY WENT OUT WITH THE CORRECT DG LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION. FROM THE WAY IT LOOKS, OUR CUSTOMER REMOVED THE DG LABELS FROM THE BOX TO SHIP AS A NON-DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: THIS IS A 49 CFR 171.15(B)(2) REPORT BECAUSE OF PACKAGE DAMAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED BY THE RECIPIENT, BUT THE INNER SHIELDED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL CONTAINER WAS MISSING FROM THE PACKAGE. IN ITEM 30 “SPILLAGE” WAS SELECTED AS MOST CLOSELY DESCRIBING THE MISSING INNER CONTAINER FROM THE PACKAGE, ALTHOUGH THERE WAS NO ACTUAL “SPILLAGE” OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL PER SE. INVESTIGATION SHOWED THE PACKAGE ARRIVED INTACT AT THE FED-EX EXPRESS LOS ANGELES RAMP. EXTENSIVE SEARCHES WERE CONDUCTED AT THE DESTINATION FED-EX EXPRESS STATION, BURA, USING APPROPRIATE RADIATION DETECTION INSTRUMENTATION, AND AT THE FED-EX EXPRESS LOS ANGELES RAMP. VEHICLES WHICH MAY HAVE BEEN INVOLVED IN THE MOVEMENT OF THE PACKAGE FROM THE FED-EX EXPRESS LOS ANGELES RAMP TO THE PACKAGE DESTINATION, ECKERT & ZIEGLER, WERE ALSO SEARCHED. THE INNER SHIELDED CONTAINER HAS NOT BEEN FOUND AND IT IS ASSUMED THAT IT ENDED UP IN TRASH AND SENT TO A LAND FILL. LAND FILL OPERATORS HAVE REPORTED AND TRASH FROM FED-EX EXPRESS FACILITIES HAVING SET OFF THEIR RADIATION MONITORS.

column168: ON 01 MARCH 2018, L3 MUSTANG TECHNOLOGY L.P. (“MUSTANG”) PREPARED A SHIPPING CONTAINER OF WHAT WAS BELIEVED TO BE TEST FIXTURES FOR SHIPMENT TO L3 FUZING & ORDNANCE SYSTEMS (“FOS”). THESE TEST FIXTURES WERE TO BE USED BY FOS ON A CONTRACT TO MANUFACTURE ALAMO FUZE SAFE & ARM (“FSA”) DEVICES. THE TEST FIXTURES EXHIBIT NO CHARACTERISTIC REQUIRING THEM TO BE IDENTIFIED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN SHIPMENT, AS SUCH MUSTANG SHIPPED THE PACKAGE AS NON-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.   FOS RECEIVED THE SHIPMENT OF TEST FIXTURES FROM MUSTANG ON 07 MARCH 2018. UPON REVIEW OF THE TEST FIXTURES, FOS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE TEST FIXTURES CONTAINED A SINGLE FSA; THE TEST FIXTURES SHOULD HAVE BEEN EMPTY.  THE TEST FIXTURES WERE NOT SHIPPED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, THUS THE PRESENCE OF A FSA IN THE PACKAGING CONSTITUES AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT AS DEFINED BY 49 CFR 171.8. THIS INCIDENT DID NOT CAUSE OR CREATE THE LIKELIHOOD FOR INJURY, PROPERTY DAMAGE, CLOSURE OR ALTERNATION OF TRANSPORTATION ROUTES, OR ENVIRONMENTAL RELEASE. THE SHIPMENT INVOLVED ONE SINGLE FSA, WITH A TOTAL WEIGHT OF 0.00009 POUNDS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.
column169: L3 FOS IS UNFAMILIAR WITH L3 MUSTANG PROCESSES AND THEREFORE NOT ABLE TO MAKE ANY RECOMMENDATIONS FOR CHANGES TO THEIR SYSTEMS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  L3 MUSTANG HAS ACKNOWLEDGED THE INCIDENT AND IS PERFORMING AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE ROOT CAUSE PROCESS FAILURE. UPON DETERMINATION OF THE ROOT CAUSE AND ANY IDENTIFICATION OF PROCESS IMPROVEMENTS, L3 MUSTANG WILL GENERATE A CORRECTIVE ACTION PLAN TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCE. THIS MAY INCLUDE PROCESS CHANGES, ADDITIONAL PROCESS IMPLEMENTATION, TRAINING, AND SUSTAINMENT ACTIONS TO ENSURE 100% COMPLIANCE NOW AND IN THE FUTURE.

column168: VMSX 280169 was discovered leaking from the BOV on March 13, 2018 by rail yard employees. Upon further inspection the valve was secure but the leak was occurring at the flange gasket between the valve and the tank.  Approximately 5 (five) gallons of liquid was found in the rail car. The liquid was drained from the car and disposed as waste. Absorbent materials were placed inside the rail car to stabilize any remaining liquids around the BOV for the OTMA-3 trip to the tank car repair facility.
column169: BNSF recommends the rail cars be purged and cleaned prior to long-term storage. These rail cars had been in storage for over 3 years and residual product had been left or had condensed inside the rail car.

column168: GATX 2852 was discovered leaking Cresylic Acid (UN2022) from the manway at the BNSF Galesburg, IL facility on March 18, 2018. The product has a pungent odor which was noticed by BNSF employees and reported to their supervisor who called for the partial yard evacuation.  The tank car was inspected and found to have two manway bolts loose. The bolts were tightened and the evacuation was lifted. A contractor was sent to inspect the tank car and found that the manway lid gasket was deteriorated and cracked. The gasket was replaced and the tank car was cleaned prior to being released for transportation.
column169: BNSF recommends that Dakota Gasification inspect their manway gaskets carefully as part of their loading procedures.  Releases of hazardous materials are unacceptable in BNSF or any other Railroad transportation.

column168: A loose "wash-out" cap was found on top of the portable tank.  The rear discharge valve had a very slow drip/leak. The cam-lock cap's inner gasket was replaced to stop the release from the discharge valve and the wash-out cap was tightened. This stopped the leak.

column168: The driver was unloading from a multi-compartment tank trailer.  He opened the valves and nothing was flowing.  After a bit he realized he was hooked to the wrong compartment (needed to unload compartment 1 and was hooked to compartment 2 and two was now empty).  He was getting 'flustered' in the confusion and when he went to hook to the correct compartment and forgot the step where we always bleed any pressure and product off of the valves to ensure its safe before removing the cap over the external valve.  1 pint sprayed out impacting his chemical suit.  Some sprayed up under his face shield which was partially up and did not have his goggles as directed by the work assignment.  He admitted he knew this was wrong but he was hot and sweating and figured it was safe since product hadn't been flowing.  He went to the eyewash station and felt like he was ok afterwards.  The next day he woke up and had some irritation in his eyes.  He then went to an urgent care facility who had him transported over to a clinci in Winschester, Va.  They found a surface burn on the eye.  Since then he has fully recovered and has no further issues with his eyes.
column169: The driver ultimately decided to resign and retire.  He was close as it was and he now felt it was time as he was having issues moving hoses and stuff around as well.  We feel there is no further action neccessary at this time.

column168: DRIVER WAS OFF-LOADING DIESEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND TANK UTILIZING A PUMP SYSTEM FROM DELIVERY TRUCK TO STATIONARY TANK AT GAS STATION. DRIVER FAILED TO PLACE VIBRATION CLAMPS AROUND CAM-LOCK CLAMPS ON DISCHARGE LINE. HOSE VIBRATED THE CLAMPS WHILE PUMP WAS RUNNING AND THE CAM-LOCK CLAMPS RELEASED CAUSING THE HOSE TO COME OFF BRIEFLY. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FLOWED OUT ONTO THE ASPHALT WHICH WAS IN POOR/WEATHERED CONDITION MAKING IT SOFT. FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED NOTIFIED THE CITY TO BRING A LARGE AMOUNT OF SAND OVER TO ASSIST IN CLEANUP. THIS SAND CONTRIBUTED TO THE LARGE EXPENSE AS IT WAS CONTAMINATED.
column169: TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE WE HAVE DONE THE FOLLOWING.    1. PROVIDED EXTRA TRAINING TO ALL DRIVERS WITH REGARDS TO CORRECT PUMP OPERATIONS WITH AN EMPHASIS ON MAKING SURE ALL COUPLINGS ARE SECURED WITH A SECONDARY STRAPPING DEVICE.    2.IMPLEMENTED POLICY THAT ALL DRIVERS MUST BE TRAINED SPECIFICALLY FOR PUMP JOBS AFTER THEY HAVE COMPLETED 6 MONTHS OF GRAVITY DROP JOBS.    3. PROVIDED OUR DISPATCHERS WITH A LIST OF APPROVED PUMP JOB OPERATORS FOR SITES WHICH REQUIRE PUMPING TO OFF-LOAD.    OVERALL WE IMPROVED OUR OPERATING PROCEDURES.

column168: THE ADVANTAGE TANK LINES, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE HOSE ADAPTOR AND THE STORAGE TANK BECAME COMPROMISED AND APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED. EMS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: ADVANTAGE TANK LINES, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: THE JACK B. KELLEY LLC DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO COMMENCE HIS DELIVERY OF LIQUID NATURAL GAS. A NUT ON A VALVE STEM WAS LOOSE WHICH PREVENTED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING THE REPAIRS, LIQUID NATURAL GAS SUDDENLY BEGAN TO ESCAPE FROM AN OPEN VALVE. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN 10 GALLONS WAS RELEASED. AN EMPLOYEE OF OUR CUSTOMER WAS STANDING BEHIND THE TRAILER WHEN THE LIQUID NATURAL GAS BEGAN TO BE RELEASED AND WAS SPRAYED. THE EMPLOYEE SUFFERED BURN INJURIES AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE WE BELIEVED HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY CUSTOMER PERSONNEL. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: JACK B. KELLEY LLC WILL NO LONGER ALLOW UNTRAINED EMPLOYEES PERFORM REPAIRS SUCH AS THIS. FURTHER, JACK B. KELLEY, LLC WILL ENSURE THAT THERE ARE NO PEOPLE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WITHOUT PROPER PPE.

column168: Original comments:   Pkg was pulled off IC belt for appearing to be leaking from within. Outer packaging had Corrosive label and info for "UN1760, Corrosive Liquid n.o.s., (contains Ammonium Hydroxide, Methylene Chloride)" on outside of pkg. The Corrosive label and other markings were covered by a colored tape or a wrap of some kind as to cover the label and markings. When pkg was opened up for inspection, a single can of Heat Flex Hi-Temp 1200 grey paint was packed inside. Looking up the SDS information to find it is UN1263. The paint can did not have any paint can clips on the lid, which allowed for lid to come open on one side and leak into bottom of pkg. An OP-117 improper shipping form has been submitted, along with a DPR/SCMS. Awaiting disposition    New Comments:

column168: The customer site gauge was broken so there weren't a good means of telling how much product was in the container.  On this account, they require the use of low air pressure (5-10psi) as their products foam very easily.  The driver did not follow his traning and left the air pressure build to max working pressure (30psi).  As a result, the product foamed and shot out the top of the tank.  When the foam settled there was roughly 20-30 percent headspace.

column168: MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT- V1 WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HWY 29 NEAR ELLISVILLE, MS. V1 WAS ENTERING A CURVE AND CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE RUMBLE STRIP ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY AND THEN STEERED TO THE LEFT TO AVOID RUNNING OFF OF THE ROAD. THIS STEERING ACTION CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO MOVE AND THE FORCE OF THE MOVEMENT CAUSED THE TANKER AND TRUCK TO START TO ROLL TO THE RIGHT. V1 LEFT THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT AND ROLLED OVER. THIS RESULTED IN SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE TO THE TRUCK AND TANKER AND A PRODUCT LEAK FROM THE WASH OUT CAPS ON THE TANKER.  POLICE DEPARTMENT AND FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED INITIALLY. E3 ENVIRONMENTAL WAS INITIATED TO THE SCENE FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE, CLEAN-UP, PRODUCT TRANSFER AND REMEDIATION. SUBSEQUENTLY, A CALL WAS PLACED TO NRC DUE TO ROAD CLOSURE AND EVACUATION. MS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WAS NOTIFIED. ALSO, CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH (CTEH) WAS INITIATED TO CONDUCT AIR AND SOIL SAMPLING IN THE AREA. TWENTY AIR SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AND RESULTED IN NO DETECTION OF PHENOL.  E3 ENVIRONMENTAL COMPLETED THE PRODUCT TRANSFER ONTO ANOTHER TANKER AND THE INITIAL CLEANUP BY APPROXIMATELY 03:00 ON 03/04/18. REMAINDER OF LOAD WAS SUCCESSFULLY DELIVERED. UPON COMPLETION OF PRODUCT TRANSFER AND INITIAL CLEAN UP THE ROAD WAS OPENED.

column168: The operator of tractor/cargo tank failed to properly secure center manhole cover on tanker.  Operator tightened closure wing nuts on passenger side first, creating a small gap between the manhole and cover on the driver-side manhole.  Surge of liquid in the cargo tank forced release of approximately 2 gallons of crude oil from the tank and into the "crows nest" on top of the tanker.  While in route to the destination, driver observed discoloration on the side of the cargo tank and he left the roadway to inspect the tank.  Driver re-secured the closure nuts on the center manhole.  Company spill response crew was dispatched and arrived to assist driver in wiping side of tanker with absorbent pads.  No evidence of contamination was observed on roadway.
column169: 1.) Revised company standard operating procedure (SOP) for securing manholes on cargo tanks.  SOP revised to provide more detailed procedure, including: "secure dome lid wing nuts by following a cross pattern sequence of tightening 1 wing nut and then tightening the one on the opposite side. Repeat sequence until all are secured."    2.) Distribute SOP and provide guidance to all drivers who operate cargo tanks regarding best practices for securing cargo tank manholes.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver was eastbound on SR-190 at approximately 55 mph and was descending the east side of Towne Pass.  As the vehicle stated descending the grade and a curve, the driver observed 3 vehicles in front of him and traveling at a slower than the posted speed limit.  The driver made a decision to turn his vehicle to the right and out into the open desert to avoid running into the rear of the vehicles in front of him.  The driver ran onto the south side of SR-190, struck a guide post and continued out into the open desert.  The vehicle overturned onto its left side. The tractor subsequently caught fire.  The tank leaked product.  California Highway Patrol immediately notified (CHP Report # 9825-2018-00062).  Immediate notification made to Office of Environmental Services (OES Control # 18-1635)   On scene were CHP, Fire Department, Cal-Trans, and National Park Services.
column169: During the Management Team Investigation we found this accident to be preventable and driver error.  While the driver was well within the posted speed limit, we feel he may have been traveling too fast for conditions.  The driver will serve the following disciplinary actions; retrained with a driver trainer, receive a final written warning, serve a suspension, and be put on probation through 4/12/2019.  Should another incident occur within the year, the driver will be terminated from all driving privileges.

column168: At 11:55 ET, ERTS received a call from Danny Fernandez who is with Dupre Logistics. Caller stated while Edward Almanza was loading his tractor / trailer (7618 / 71009) at a well site, with UN1267 Petroleum Crude Oil when his hose cupping came loose releasing approximately 25-40 gallons impacted the soil behind the trucks tanker. He stated that the driver used his entire spill kit to try and contain the release but needed a contractor to be dispatch to assist in the clean up activities. Contractor confirmed that 20 Gallons of material released to hard packed gravel soil which confirmed the need to only dig approximately 2 inches of the soil. Spill extends 50'x20' in some areas. A roll off box was brought on site and the impacted soil was remediated, total of 6-10 cubic yards of soil generated from this response. Contractor utilized soil from the area to back-fill and grade the remediated areas. A degreaser solution was used on the tin wall where the drain pipe is to remove some staining but appears there are previous stains on the same area. There is no further cleanup needed.

column168: RDWY 127740 was discovered by BNSF employees leaking in the Willow  Springs, IL intermodal facility. The container was moved to the Hazmat Pit and inspected by a contractor.  The contractor discovered that the load had shifted and punctured a plastic drum of Potassium Hydroxide. Approximately half the drum leaked out before the leak could be stopped. The drum was overpacked and the spilled product cleaned up.  The load in the container was re-packaged and re-secured for return back to YRC.
column169: BNSF recommends YRC review their loading requirements for hazardous materials and make sure that loading personnel double check that each load is secured properly prior to release for transportation.  Releases of hazardous materials are unacceptable on BNSF during transit.

column168: PROX 31710 was reported emanting vapors in the BNSF Railyard on 3/21/2018.  After inspection is was reported PROX 31710 was releasing product from the pressure relief device due to the car being overloaded and PROX 31710 pressure relief device (PRD) "O" rings being damaged.  PROX 31710 load was reduced and the PRD "O" rings were replaced to stop any further release.

column168: During routine inspections and while engaged in the offloading process, facility personnel identified a release from a compromised container. In appropriate personal protective equipment, facility personnel were successful in repacking the contents into another appropriately rated container. It was then identified that the container was missing a liner, integral to the containers ability to withstand the rigors of transportation. The waste was sent to its final destination facility without further incident. A courtesy report to Texas Commission on Environmental Quality was made to Operator Rosie on 03/16/2018 at 15:16 CST resulting in report #2018-1011.
column169: The generator was made aware of the release, counselled on proper container inspections and preparation for transport, as well as provided an abundance of material for future loads.  The driver was counselled on having a clear dialogue with the generator with each pickup, to ensure boxes are fully prepared for transportation.

During routine facility offloading procedures, a container was identified to have been compromised. In appropriate personal protective equipment, facility personnel were successful in containing the release; transport trailer impacted only, no water ways, soil, or storm drains in the vicinity. The closure on the container was secured properly, the trailer was restored and the container was sent to its final destination without further incident. A courtesy notification was made to the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality to operator Tonya Owens and report #2018-1085 was generated.
column169: An internal investigation was launched and all parties involved with the loading and transportation of the compromised container was counselled and re-trained on the importance of following container closure procedures to manufacturers specification.

column168: ON MARCH 26TH, OUR DRIVER REPORTED TO WORK HOOKED UP TO LANGER TRAILER #761. HE DID HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AT OUR JERSEY CITY, NEW JERSEY TERMINAL. UPON COMPLETING HIS INSPECTION, HE WENT TO IMTT IN BAYONNE, TO LOAD A SHIPMENT OF ISOPAR K. HIS TRAILER WAS LOADED AND WHEN HE PULLED OFF THEIR SCALE AND STOPPED IN FRONT OF THE DISPATCH OFFICE THE FRONT WASH OUT CAP CAME OFF THE TRAILER. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT UP TO 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF THE WASHOUT CAP AND ONTO THE GROUND. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THE DRIVER AND CLEANED UP BY IMTT PERSONNEL USING SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBENT PADS. OUR DRIVER WAS RELEASED FROM THE SCENE ONCE THE WASHOUT CAP WAS PROPERLY FASTENED DOWN ON THE TRAILER. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES TO REPORT.  WE DELIVERED THE LOAD TO THE CUSTOMER WITHOUT ANY FURTHER INCIDENTS. ONCE THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO THE YARDS WE INSPECTED THE WASH OUT CAP AND THE PORT THAT IT SCREWS INTO AND DIDN’T FIND ANYTHING WRONG WITH THE TRAILER. ADDITIONALLY, WE INTERVIEWED THE DRIVER AND HE STATES THAT HE CHECKED ALL OF THE WASH OUT CAPS ON THE TRAILER DURING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND THEY WERE ALL TIGHT AND SECURE. BASED ON HIS STATEMENT AND OUR FINDINGS ON THE TRAILER WE BELIEVED THAT THE WASHOUT CAP CAME OFF BECAUSE IT WAS CROSS THREADED AND CONTRIBUTE THIS INCIDENT TO HUMAN ERROR.
column169: DRIVER WAS IMMEDIATELY SENT FOR POST ACCIDENT DRUG/ALCOHOL TESTING. HE WAS THEN BROUGHT INTO THE OFFICE THE NEXT MORNING AND THE EVENTS WERE REVIEWED WITH HIM. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED AND RETRAINED ON WHAT IS HIS RESPONSIBILITY IS WHEN IT COMES TO SECURING CLEAN-OUT CAPS. HE WAS SHOWN PROPER METHOD FOR SEALING THE CAPS AND ISSUED A SPANNER WRENCH TO ENSURE TIGHT FIT. A INTERNAL INCIDENT/ACCIDENT REPORT WAS FILED AND THE DRIVERS PERSONNEL FILE NOTATED WITH THE EVENTS. A LETTER WAS ISSUED TO THE DRIVER TO DOCUMENT THE INCIDENT. LANGER TRANSPORT WILL SHARE THIS EVENT WITH THE FLEET AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.

column168: VEHICLE NUMBER 3 HAD BEEN IN AN EARLIER CRASH THAT HAD OCCURRED AT 3:05 AM ON STATE HWY 121 INVOLVING IT RUNNING THE REAR OF ANOTHER TRACTOR TRAILER. VEHICLE NUMBER 3 REMAINED IN THE CENTER OF THE HWY WHEN VEHICLE 1 AND VEHICLE 2 CAME ON THE SCENE STRIKING THE REAR OF VEHICLE NUMBER 3. VEHICLES 1 & 2 OVERTURNED GOING TOWARD THE CENTER MEDIUM. VEHICLE 2 WHEN PASSING OVER VEHICLE 3 HAD ITS TANK TRIPPED OPEN BY SHARP POINTS FROM VEHICLE NUMBER 3. BOTH UNITS 1 & 2 ENDED UP ON THEIR SIDES AND PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ON THE HWY ITSELF, AND THE GRASSIE SIDE OF THE HWY. THE CLEANING GUYS WERE CALLED OUT BY NTTA, AND CURA WAS CALLED IN BY FRONTIER TANK LINES. EMS WAS CALLED OUT TO DO THE WORK BY CURA. CLEANING HAS BEEN GOING ON SINCE THE ACCIDENT, DUE TO THE AMOUNT OF RAIN WE HAVE HAD IN THE AREA SINCE THE ACCIDENT.
column169: ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED DUE TO SLOW RESPONSE BY EMERGENCY RESPONDER FORM NTTA, CARROLLTON FIRE DEPARTMENT, CARROLLTON POLICE, LEWISVILLE POLICE, AND THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION. ACCIDENT NUMBER ONE OCCURRED AT 3:05 AM. CALL INTO 911 WAS MADE AT 3:10. OUR VEHICLE CAME INTO THE AREA AND DIDN’T SEE THE BLACK BMW IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD. A CITIZEN WAS ON THE SHOULDER FLASHING A FLASH LIGHT AND THIS DISTRACTED OUR DRIVER WHICH CAUSED HIM TO BE LOOKING TO THE RIGHT INSTEAD OF STRAIGHT AHEAD. HAD EMERGENCY RESPONDER LIGHTS WERE GOING TO INFORM OF THE DANGER AHEAD THIS ACCIDENT WOULD NOT OF OCCURRED. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS DIDN’T SHOW UP FOR ANOTHER 10 MINUTES AFTER OUR DRIVER HAD COLLIDED WITH THE REAR END OF THE BLACK BMW.  ACTION NEEDED IS A BETTER RESPONSE TIME BY EMERGENCY RESPONDER. 39 MINUTES IN AN AREA THAT IS WELL REPRESENTED BY EMERGENCY RESPONDERS, WHICH SHOULD HAVE BEEN 14 MINUTES, WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS ACCIDENT.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. DOME LID OF THE TANKER OPENED DURING TRANSPORT TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY. AS A RESULT APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS WERE RELEASED AND IMPACTED THE ROAD SURFACE AND TANKER. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DELAWARE COUNTY EMA RESPONDED TO INCIDENT. FIRST RESPONDERS DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUID. GREEN CHARGE, INC. WAS DISPATCHED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP. GREEN CHARGE, INC. ARRIVED AND CONFIRMED THAT THE FREE LIQUID WAS CONTAINED ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE. GREEN CHARGE, INC. WIPED DOWN THE IMPACTED TANKER AND RECOVERED THE SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL. GREEN CHARGE, INC. WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, VICKERY TRANSPORTATION, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: The cargo tank semi-trailer was cleaned and purged for jet fuel delivery service.  The semi-trailer was returned to our terminal with the top manholes unsecured.  Maintenance personnel failed to check tightness of the top manhole covers before placing the semi-trailer in service.  Driver picked up the unit and drove to loading facility.  When leaving loading facility, jet fuel sloshed out of the unsecured manhole covers.  The 25 gallons of jet fuel flowed off the rear top and fell to the roadway.  First responders closed the roadway during pavement clean up.

column168: ERTS was notified by Schneider Bulk of a 200gal release of UN3266 Corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s. 8 PGIII from a bulk tanker (24638) a 307/304 type tanker. The driver was making a delivery when the hose disconnected causing the release and impacting an asphalt parking lot. The driver did not have the hose connected properly. The caller stated that there is a storm drain in the area but at this time there are no reports of impact. The RQ for sodium hypochlorite is 1000lb at this time there is only a 200lb release so no regulatory reporting will be required.Contractors report cleanup is complete and they are leaving site. All spilled product was recovered with a vacuum unit and then cleaned/ solidified with granular absorbents and a sweeper unit. Nonhaz waste generated and taken offsite:  9 - 55 gal poly drums of impacted absorbents/ solids.   1 - 55 gal poly drum of diluted liquid.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0715 HOURS ON MARCH 14, 2018, A THIRD-PARTY CARRIER, ALEY & L GROUP CORPORATION, WAS FILLING THEIR TANKER TRUCK WITH PG 70-10 PAVING ASPHALT (ASPHALT).  WHILE LOADING, APPROXIMATELY  20 BARRELS OF ASPHALT SPILLED WITHIN A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA. NO WATERWAYS OR OFF-SITE LANDS WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. ASPHALT LOADING OPERATIONS IN THE AREA WERE STOPPED AND THE SHIFT SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED.  THE AREA WAS SECURED AND CORRESPONDING FEDERAL AND STATE AGENCIES WERE CONTACTED. THE TANKER TRUCK WAS DECONTAMINATED PRIOR TO LEAVING THE FACILITY. CLEAN-UP WAS CONDUCTED BY IN-HOUSE PERSONNEL; MOST OF THE MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED BY MELTING BACK INTO THE PROCESS AND THE REMAINING WAS DISPOSED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.   AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION, WORF CONCLUDED THAT THE TANKER CONTAINED WATER PRIOR TO LOADING PG 70-10 AT 350F. THE RESIDUAL WATER EXPANDED RAPIDLY AND FORCED PRODUCT TO BOIL OVER FROM THE TANKER ONTO THE GROUND.
column169: MANAGEMENT CONTACTED ALEY & L GROUP FOR ASSURANCE THE TANKER AND DRIVER WOULD NOT RETURN UNTIL INCIDENT INVESTIGATION AND RE-TRAINING WERE COMPLETED.

column168: UNDECLARED PACKAGE DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY. THIS SHIPMENT HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

A phenol railcar was overloaded for transport.  In the event of steaming the railcar some phenol (100 lbs) burped out of the top manway into our containment dike.  The team had to offload enough of the material so it could be shipped to our customer.  The railcar and containment area was cleaned and the loaders proceeded to offload the railcar back into a process tank.
column169: Performed an investigation into the spill and made several recommendations to prevent any occurrence of an overflow out of the railcar.  The team will reduce our steam from 190 pounds pressure to 100 pounds.  The procedure will be updated with this change.  The procedure will also be updated to reflect either unloading the railcar the day an overload occurs or the very the next day.  This will reduce the amount of time the railcar would be on steam as the phenol should stay in a fairly good molten state within that time frame.  The other update to the procedure is to reinforce the monitoring of all railcars when they reach a certain percent in the railcar. The goal is zero overloads on any railcars.

column168: On 3/26/18 at approximately 2:30 PM a Langer Transport truck was traveling within the IMTT terminal.  As the driver applied his brakes the load (Isopar K) pushed against the wash out cap which caused the cap to pop off and released approximately 5 gallons of product out and down the side of the tanker compartment.  The driver got out and properly secured the cap.  US Ecology (IMTT's OSRO) was called and responded with a crew to clean up the tanker compartment and the area around the truck.  IMTT's Emergency Response Team (ERT) was also dispatched to the area to standby.
column169: IMTT contacted the customer of the product that was released and reported the incident. The customer will follow up with the transporter to address any driver errors or structural defects that may have lead to this incident.

column168: On March 29, 2018, at 1450 hours, a local citizen in Palmetto, GA, reported a suspicious odor coming from tank car ITDX 135207, a load of Sulfur.  The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via Canutec Report 613-996-6666. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched the scene and found a vapor release due to a misaligned gasket on the manway cover.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Neil Fehr, with Co-Operative Refinery.  After inspecting the manway cover gasket for defects, HEPACO was able to re-secure the manway cover with the gasket properly installed.  This secured the vapor release and the car was release for transportation.    NAR Cause Code: 208 NARRI: 5(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60
column169: (NAR Cause Code: 208)

column168: While loading cargo, one fibreboard drum was nicked by the side of the cargo compartment doorway latch mechanism of the forward cargo compartment of the aircraft.  The fine powdered substance, which is a surfactant, spilled from the hole created in the side of the drum.  The size of the hole was approximately the size of a tennis ball to a baseball.  Airline Management was contacted and the Lead Environmental Coordinator contacted a local Environmental Response company to come to PHL airport for cleanup.  Miller's Environmental of Philadelphia responded at 21:17 and cleaned up the spilled substance using an industrial vacuum with a Hepa filter.  A Ramp employee who was Asthmatic inhaled some of the powder and was transported to the hospital for examination and treatment.  She had an adverse reaction to the medications and was admitted to the hospital for 4 days.
column169: A bit more attention to detail/care could have been taken by the loader operator to ensure the shipment did not brush against the side of the cargo compartment opening.  The damage occurred to the side of the shipment opposite from the loader operator and was therefore difficult to see without stopping and walking to the other side of the loader to check for clearance.  This would not be normal procedure. The drums on the pallet may have been a bit "oversize" requiring extra attention and care to load.  Although not required, an extra wrap or cardboard around the fibre drums might have prevented this incident but that is also unknown.  The drums were wrapped in heavy plastic wrap.

At 04:10 ET, ERTS received a call from Bobbi Zerfas at XPO terminal (XSW). The caller stated that while they were unloading trailer (3178864) a forklift operator punctured (1) 55-gallon poly drum containing UN2920, Corrosive Liquid, Flammable, N.O.S., 8, (3), PGII (Quaternary Ammonium Compound, Ethanol). column168: ON 3/14/18 A PRELOAD SUPERVISOR WAS ATTEMPTING TO RESEAL A PACKAGE AT 08:55 WHEN THE PACKAGE STARTED TO BURN. THE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY EXTINGUISHED THE PACKAGE WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER. THE ONLY DAMAGE WAS TO THE PACKAGE FROM THE FIRE NO EVACUATION AND NO INJURIES OCCURRED FROM THE PACKAGE FIRE. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED A PORTABLE POWER JUMP STARTER BEING RETURNED TO A SNAP-ON REPAIR CENTER. IT APPEARS THE FIRE STARTED FROM THE CABLES ARCING ON THE JUMP STARTER.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: Original comments:   Driver brought over package stating it was leaking liquid metal.  Upon inspection, QA found 2 bottles of pure mercury.  1 was leaking.  QA collected material for manager inspection later this evening.    New Comments:  Contents are two 1-lb. bottles of ?triple distilled chemically pure mercury? as manufactured by Jelinek Alloys Div. and I. Stern Products Corp. It appears the two small boxes were packaged in a USPS padded mailer, which was packed inside another USPS mailer, which was then packed into the small fiberboard box in which it moved through our network. The outer package has no markings of any kind other than the label. Based on approximate weight of the two small boxes the bottles are contained in, I would surmise that one of the bottles lost approximately half of its volume of mercury? roughly 0.5 pounds.
